{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489608","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489608"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:22:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:22:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"700"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/700"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.07,0.48,0.02,0.28]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"700"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38511"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/700"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"700"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22936"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"423"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2785"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2879"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/38511"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner with a new onset of flashes of light in her left eye. She then notices a large number of persistent spots in front of her left eye. She has a history of hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. On examination, she has a normal visual acuity bilaterally, with normal visual fields and no relative afferent pupillary defect.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Central retinal vein occlusion","Migraine","Posterior vitreous detachment","Acute angle closure glaucoma","Retinal detachment"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient presents with an acute onset of flashes and floaters. The most common cause of this presentation is a \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior vitreous detachment\u003C/strong\u003E. Some two-thirds of individuals over the age of 70 will experience some degree of posterior vitreous detachment. This detachment occurs due to age-related shrinkage of the vitreous \u0027pulling\u0027 on the retina causing flashes of light. Posterior pieces of the posterior vitreous face now float in front of the retina. The moving shadows from these cause the annoying floaters, which sink with gravity in time. Patients with posterior vitreous detachment are at a high risk of a retinal detachment if there is an associated vitreous haemorrhage. This patient will require ophthalmoscopy and a slit lamp examination to clarify and confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetinal detachment\u003C/strong\u003E is relatively rare event, however it does need to be excluded in patients presenting with an acute onset of flashes and floaters. This patient requires same day ophthalmological referral for a dilated fundus examination to exclude a retinal detachment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentral retinal vein occlusion\u003C/strong\u003E presents with painless vision loss and a fundus with haemorrhages in all quadrants. \u003Cstrong\u003EMigraine\u003C/strong\u003E can cause flashes of lights, however it is likely to present with bilateral visual disturbances associated with a headache. \u003Cstrong\u003EAcute angle closure glaucoma\u003C/strong\u003E will typically present with a unilateral painful eye, with reduced visual acuity and a mid-dilated unresponsive pupil.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Although the most common cause of flashes and floaters is a posterior vitreous detachment, ophthalmological referral is required to exclude a retinal detachment."],"references":["Kahawita S, Simon S, Gilhotra J. Flashes and floaters A practical approach to assessment and management. Australian Family Physician 2014;43:201-3."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22936"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"700"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/22936"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-07-30T10:30:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2023-07-30T10:30:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"700"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38511"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","l